  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Two surveys are conducted. 1) a representative survey of the public's perception towards
      organ donation and 2) different messages to examine effect on family members'
      decision-making.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      We aim to replicate the models presented in Sanner (1994; 2006), which categorise people's
      attitudes and reactions to the topic of organ donation. Anti-donation reaction patterns can
      be viewed in terms of: 1) the illusion of lingering life, 2) protection of the individual's
      value, 3) distrust of healthcare, 4) nature's border, 5) the border of identity, and 6)
      issues of transcendence. On the other hand, pro-donation reaction patterns can be viewed in
      terms of: 1) altruism, and 2) facticity.

      Sources:

        -  Sanner, M. (1994). Attitudes toward organ donation and transplantation: A model for
           understanding reactions to medical procedures after death. Social Science &amp; Medicine,
           38(8), 1141-1152.

        -  Sanner, M. A. (2006). People's attitudes and reactions to organ donation. Mortality,
           11(2), 133-150.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
